<font color="#FF0000">REMEMBERING OUR BROTHER </font><br>
<tt>Thu Dec 18 17:44:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br><br>
Dear Regina<br><br>
Thank you for your kind words. <br><br>
Sobering thoughts for this time of the year.<br><br>
I was no longer in country when your brother was killed, but you are a part of a family of warriors that believed in our country and in what we did.<br><br>
Your family is our family, your hurt, ours, your lost, our country's, deepest lost.<br><br>
Thank you, Regina, thank you for posting and for keeping us mindful of why we are here.  We are here for you and for each other. <br><br>
Healing begins with sharing the love and care we had then, with families and friends of those who served and died by our sides. <br><br>
Our memories, from yesterday and today will prevent tomorrow’s sorrows. If the spirit that resides in you on this day was present in your brother in Vietnam, there are many others that remember him as well. He remains part of what made this country great and what is important today.<br><br>
A Marine died in my place while I was in Vietnam, and I've often wondered what would have happened if he had lived, what a family he would have had. Everyday, I remember him by being grateful for the gift of a family God has given. For my wife, five daughters and two sons.<br><br>
Thank you, for sharing.<br><br>
In Peace and War<br><br>
Cook Barela, Sgt. USMC Republic of Vietnam June 1967-July 1968<br>

